Methods
Cortical synaptic plasticity depends on many factors such as:
Implementing a phenomenological voltage based model of STDP4,5 in a morphologically realistic neuron model6 to study experimentally observed location dependence of STDP.
Model of Synaptic Plasticity
A phenomenological voltage-based model depending on the presynaptic spike time and the time course of the postsynaptic membrane potential which is filtered with different time constants4,5.
Neuron Model

A detailed representation of the neocortical pyramidal cells in layer 5 (L5PCs)6. It is a morphologically realistic model containing several ion channels giving rise to active dendritic properties which affect backpropagating action potentials (BAPs). The model is based on the experimental data from the soma and dendrites of the L5PCs characterizing their firing properties in their two different spiking zones (somatic region: Na+ APs; distal apical dendrites: Ca2+ spikes).
Stimulation Protocols
Figure 1. Schema of the STDP rule.
Figure 2. Reconstructed morphology of a L5b neocortical pyramidal cell.
blue: proximal dendrite; red: distal denrite

Quadruple whole cell recordings from thick tufted L5 neurons of rat visual cortex using different frequencies (0.1, 10, 20, 40, 50 Hz) and by using precisely timed pre- and postsynaptic APs seperated by 10 ms2. This configuration is repeated 15 times for each pair.
Simultaneous recordings from L5 to L5 and L2/3 to L5 connections by pairing five EPSPs and APs 15 times at a frequency of 50 Hz and with the precise timing of pre before post firing by 10 ms3.
Application of the phenomenological STDP rule to a compartmental L5b cortical pyramidal cell model.
Close reproduction of Sjstrm et al. (2001, 2006) experimental findings without fundamental modification of the STDP rule.
We conclude that an STDP rule that does not vary with dendritic location is consistent with all experimental observations and predicts an observed dendritic switch with distance from the soma.
Better fits may be acquired with additional factors in the rule that make up for certain limitations regarding differences between compartmental and point neuron models.
